Vaccination applied in Kuban following an outbreak of avian flu in wild birds
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
In connection with the suspected outbreak of avian influenza in wild birds in the Temryuk district of Krasnodar region [Kuban; see commentary], veterinarians will carry out vaccination of poultry.

As reported by YuGA.ru, about 1000 dead birds have been found on the shores of the Black Sea and Azov sea. According to preliminary data, the birds have died of bird flu [confirmed in the meantime; see item 2].

"Poultry will be vaccinated within the so-called endangered zone, although we have not imposed quarantine," the deputy head of the district administration of Rosselkhoznadzor, Alexander Malakhov, told RIA Novosti.

Also, according to the deputy chief of the department, because of the outbreak in the wild birds, inspections are to be carried out on poultry farms in Kuban. "We will double-check their compliance with the law," he said. He also added that the monitoring will include shooting birds in the region, "to check whether the virus is circulating."

According to Malakhov, avian flu has not been present in the region since 2006. He did not rule out the possibility that the virus at this time was in the region due to the seasonal migration of wild birds.

Source (machine translated): Yuga http://www.yuga.ru/news/adygea/index.shtml.

