[We are grateful to the communicator, Gert van der Hoek, FluTrackers, for both reports and for his added information: "Other reports mention additional affected wild bird species, like coots and swans."

The vaccination of humans, referred to in the above report, deserves to be clarified. Animal H5N1 vaccines are commercially available and in wide use in several countries. Though some H5N1 vaccines for humans have been developed or are under testing, to the best of our knowledge they have not been certified and/or not (yet) available on the (civilian) market, for general public use.

The Krasnodar Territory administrative division in southeastern European Russia, extends from the Sea of Azov and the Black Sea into the Kuban steppe and straddles the northwestern end of the Greater Caucasus. For a map of the Kuban region, sometimes referred to as Krasnodar, see map at http://tinyurl.com/c4u9d3m.

Anapa is a seaport town in the Krasnodar Region in southwest Russia. It is located on the northern coast of the Black Sea near the Sea of Azov (map at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/RS/38/Anapa.html).

An administrative map of Russia is available at http://www.eegas.com/images/11-legend.gif (Krasnodar at the south-west).

H5N1 outbreak, involving wild birds and domestic poultry, was last recorded in the region in January 2007. The Azov Sea basin is situated on a main flyway of various species of migrating birds. - Mod.AS]
